{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"bdfaffa9-bff8-4fb0-8032-dc0c4ac08013","content":"Yes, both are known MSTest v4 breaking changes. Here's the rundown:\n\n---\n\n### 1. Lost test history in Azure DevOps\n\nMSTest v4 changed the **default fully-qualified test ID** format. Azure DevOps correlates history by test ID, so every test looks \"new.\" You can restore the old IDs by adding to your `.runsettings`:\n\n```xml\n<MSTest>\n  <TestIdGenerationStrategy>DisplayName</TestIdGenerationStrategy>\n</MSTest>\n```\n\nOr set the legacy strategy via an MSBuild property if you prefer.\n\n---\n\n### 2. `TestContext.TestName` in `[ClassInitialize]`\n\nIn v4, the `TestContext` passed to `[ClassInitialize]` is a **class-level context** — it's no longer tied to any specific test. Accessing `TestName` now throws `InvalidOperationException`.\n\n**Fix for your code** — guard against it or remove the access:\n\n```csharp\n[ClassInitialize]\npublic static void ClassInit(TestContext context)\n{\n    // context.TestName is not available here in v4\n    // Use context.FullyQualifiedTestClassName instead, or\n    // move per-test logic to [TestInitialize].\n}\n```\n\n---\n\n### 3. Other key v4 changes to watch for\n\n| Area | What changed |\n|---|---|\n| **`[DataRow]` type coercion** | Implicit type conversions (e.g., `int` → `long`) are stricter; mismatches may fail at runtime. |\n| **`Assert.AreEqual` on doubles** | Floating-point tolerance comparison was tightened; some previously-passing assertions may now fail. |\n| **`[DeploymentItem]`** | Deployment behavior changed; files may not copy to the test output dir the same way. |\n| **Parallel execution** | Class-level parallelism is now the default. Tests that relied on serial execution may see race conditions. Add `[Parallelize(Scope = ExecutionScope.MethodLevel)]` or disable if needed. |\n| **`TestContext.Properties`** | The writable property bag is more restricted; setting arbitrary keys may throw. |\n\n---\n\n### TL;DR action items for your project\n\n1. Add a `.runsettings` with `TestIdGenerationStrategy` to preserve ADO history.\n2. Remove `context.TestName` from `ClassInit` (line 13 of `SetupTests.cs`) — move that logic to a `[TestInitialize]` method if you need the test name.\n3. Audit any `[DataRow]` type mismatches and floating-point assertions.\n4. Check for tests that assume serial execution — v4 parallelizes by default.\n\nWant me to apply the fix to `SetupTests.cs`?","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"d48b7038-4689-4b45-9f3c-fdf77ae86677","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"Now I have a clear picture. Let me address the user's questions about MSTest v4 breaking changes.\n\n1. **Tests appearing as brand new in Azure DevOps** — MSTest v4 changed the default test ID generation. In v3, the \"fully qualified name\" used for test IDs was based on the method name only. In v4, the default test ID includes the full namespace + class + method, which changes how Azure DevOps tracks test history (since it uses test IDs to correlate history).\n\n2. **TestContext.TestName in [ClassInitialize]** — In MSTest v4, the `TestContext` passed to `[ClassInitialize]` is no longer associated with a specific test, so accessing `TestName` throws an `InvalidOperationException`. \n\nThat's because class initialization runs once for the entire class before any individual test executes, so there's no specific test context to reference.\n\n3. **Other things to watch out for** — There are several other known breaking changes in MSTest v4 worth being aware of.\n\nLet me put together a comprehensive answer covering these issues.","outputTokens":909},"id":"4f4ad070-59a9-43fb-9835-f7ef9c78e291","timestamp":"2026-04-03T01:29:32.636Z","parentId":"f1daf18c-6511-4f72-99a9-81150360030b"}
